INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Problem 2 - value of D: Do we consider different values of D for this question? Or we can choose one value and work with it?","You should not use any D values different then one, meaning your raw features.");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Problem1: Definition of cross-validation: Hello,I am kinda lost about cross-validation.Is the following definition of cross-validation correct: n-fold cross-validation: divide the data up into  chunks and train  times, treating a different chunk as the holdout set each time.?If so, do we need to split the test data from the given data in advance, and then split the left data into training data and test data?","In this case where we will be using cross validation to just evaluate our model and not tune parameters or choose between models its OK to just use the whole dataset for cross validation without a separate test set put aside (especially since we have so littleamount of data)Well know that I think about it better we are tuning The grade of the polynomial or lambda depending the exercise but I think we are not supposed to use a separate testing set to evaluate our model at the end.ADD ON: I think you have the basic idea of k-fold cross validation right. Here's how I think about it hopefully it'll help. Let's use k=5 as an example, and say we're trying to find a lambda value, although the same technique could be applied to find a polynomial degree. First we would split the data into 5 equal portions. For each value of lambda we are considering we would train the model 5 different times, each time "holding out" 1/5th of the data to do testing on. We would compute 5 test errors for each value of lambda, each on a different "fold" of the data, specifically the "fold" we didn't use to do fitting. The average of these 5 test errors we would define to be the test error for that particular lambda. We would then iterate to the next value of lambda and repeat. After going through all values for lambda we'd choose the one with the lowest average test error. At this point we could go back and fit the model to the entire data set using our selected value of lambda to find the parameters.");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("What should a write up be?Since this is the first time I did an assignment like this, I am not sure how to write the write up. What should a write up contain? The assignment requirement says 'Clearly denote what each function does, which problem it belongs to, and what the inputs and the outputs are' , does this need to be included in the write up?","The write-up should include only what is asked. Don't worry about formalities, when we grade the assignment we are looking for the right answers and right conclusions (or if not, at least the right approach).In terms of code, you don't need to explain your code in detail. Your code must run and actually produce the results you put in the write-up, but generally a single paragraph is enough to explain what are the files you are submitting for that specific problem. If some of these files are MATLAB functions, explain in a sentence what the function does. That's it. ");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Question 4: how do you want the binary classification error to be quantified?","It would be the count of wrong classifications divided by the total number of observations in the training set. We're looking for a percentage here.");
