INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Without giving away too much, is it sufficient in part (B) to write the feature mapping with respect to one-dimensional inputs? Arbitrary n-dimensional inputs seem to be rather nasty to try to express in this manner.I can express the logic up until the point where I actually need to write the feature mapping phi, but I lack the knowledge of notation to make the n-dimensional case succinctly.","You won't get full credit if you derive the solution for 1-dimensional data only. The d-dimensional case is actually not that hard to derive, the feature mapping phi is infinite dimensional for both 1-dimensional and d-dimensional cases and therefore you should think of inner-products as an integral (over the product) rather than a sum (of products).");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("I am having trouble understanding why the VC dimension has anything to do with the number of hypothesis existed in a given space, could somebody please help me out?","Consider the following game:You pick n points, x_1 . . . x_n. Your adversary labels those n points as they want. Let's say for the sake of simplicity that the adversary applies binary classification, labeling each of the n points as either 0 or 1. You could express your adversary's labeling as a binary string in {0,1}^n, where the first bit in that labeling corresponds to the label of the first point, the second bit corresponding to the second point, etc. Call this binary string the hypothesis of your adversary.To win the game, you must propose a concept (in our case, a classifier), which describes a means by which you can match the hypothesis of your opponent.The VC dimension in this context is then the greatest number of points you can choose that will allow you to, regardless of thehypothesis,win against your opponent in the game. Knowing the hypothesis space H is important because it defines the space of all possible hypotheses that your opponent can put forth (in the case of the game, binary strings of length n). In order to be able to shatter k points, you need to be able to match all possible hypotheses by using a concept (classifier) in your concept space ('suitcase', as Tony endearingly puts it).Hope this helps!");
