INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Every time I come to lecture, people keep talking about something called 'classifiers.'  What in the world is a classifier?Also, I've always been allowed to use multiplication tables on my previous exams.  Is it okay if I use my multiplication tables today?","A classifier is a function that, given a vector input, outputs a binary decision (either a 0 or 1 or, alternatively, a -1 or +1). We have developed several algorithms to learn good classifiers from training data. The algorithms include perceptrons, support vector machines, logistic regression, neural networks, etc.Also, no multiplication tables are allowed, but, you can definitely bring an abacus to the midterm.");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("HW3, Question 1 I can't understand part 1 of question 1 completely. Does it mean if after N rounds we conclude that the dice is most likely unfair, (which is defined when the probability that both dices are loaded is >= 0.5 ??), what is the minimum number of wins?!Thanks. ","The questions asks the minimum number of plays you have to observe, so it is possible to reach the conclusion that the dice are loaded. Notice that, even if the dice are indeed loaded, this will not necessarily happen in the minimum number of plays. It depends on the outcomes.The question ask what is this minimum number of plays and when is it sufficient to detect that the dice are not fair (which are the outcomes that allow us to do this inference in the minimum number of plays).");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Problem 2 I got a bit confused with notation in this problem. p means pdf where P means probability itself. So I cannot understand why the question uses p(H) instead of P(H), because the way I'm looking at it is given \mu, probability of head is \mu, however I know the prior distribution of \mu, so P(H) is average \mu... right?Thanks","In the homework description we are using p(H) as the probability of heads. In other words, we are using p interchangeably for pdfs and probabilities.");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Convex problems Hi all, I believe it would be interesting for everyone if we listed below all the convex minimisation (or concave maximisation) we've encountered so far in ML with some justifications for each example (as to why it is convex). Thanks all for your contribution (or any TA also)","I believe all optimization problems you have seen in class so far are convex/concave. A way of showing that is, for example, to take the likelihood and compute it's Hessian (equivalent to the second derivative). If can show that the Hessian is always negative definite, then you know the likelihood is strictly concave. Instead of maximizing the likelihood, you can minimize the negative likelihood, which is a convex optimization problem.You can do this to show that linear regression and logistic regression (with or without regularization) are convex problems. For SVM, there are other ways to show it's convexity, but it is also a convex problem.Perhaps the first non-convex roblem you will see in class is fitting mixtures of Gaussians. Because this is a non-convex problem, you will need to use the EM algorithm to try to solve it.");
INSERT INTO Intellibot.TrainingData(question,answer) VALUES("Too large data for problem 5 of hw3? When I computed  the RBF kernel parameter ?, it took very long time.  In fact, training data TrainingX is of size 1000*784, so the  running time for  ? is at least 784*10^6.  I wonder whether it is possible to do all the computation.","It should be reasonable if you vectorize your operations (as opposed to using for loops in MATLAB). Here's some links that could help: http://www.mathworks.com/help/matlab/matlab_prog/vectorization.html http://www.mathworks.com/help/matlab/matlab_prog/techniques-for-improving-performance.html As a general rule of thumb, a modern processor has at least ~25 GFLOPS per core (e.g., 25×109 floating-point operations (meaning add/subtract/divide/multiply)) per second. Thus, the operation should complete fairly quickly.");
